1
00:01:03,354 --> 00:01:04,189
Sir, it's no good!

2
00:01:04,773 --> 00:01:07,525
The flames have spread to the forest
in the Third District!

3
00:01:08,026 --> 00:01:10,528
Send more choppers! We need air support!

4
00:01:10,528 --> 00:01:12,906
At this rate, the whole mountain range
is gonna go up!

5
00:01:13,490 --> 00:01:16,534
Damn it all! I don't get how
it's covering so much ground!

6
00:01:29,547 --> 00:01:31,174
What... what's happened here?

7
00:01:38,223 --> 00:01:40,892
The trees, they're flattened.

8
00:01:40,892 --> 00:01:43,269
My God. Did something crash?

9
00:01:43,269 --> 00:01:45,980
No, sir.
No reports of one, at least.

10
00:01:49,859 --> 00:01:52,112
Where are you, Mont Blanc?
Why can't I get a signal?

11
00:01:52,112 --> 00:01:55,323
- You can't be here!
- Mont Blanc! I'm coming!

12
00:01:55,865 --> 00:01:59,160
- Professor!
- Let me go!

13
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:01,996
No, Professor!
Any closer, and you'll burn alive!

14
00:02:01,996 --> 00:02:03,998
His signal's gone dead!

15
00:02:03,998 --> 00:02:08,211
Do you know what that means?
Mont Blanc's signal has gone dead!

16
00:03:11,399 --> 00:03:13,318
What's wrong, Gesicht? I heard a gasp.

17
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:18,406
Nothing. Really.

18
00:03:19,032 --> 00:03:19,991
I'm fine, dear.

19
00:03:19,991 --> 00:03:22,452
It seems like you've been so tired lately.

20
00:03:22,452 --> 00:03:26,497
I hope you're not working too hard.
Some time off might do you good.

21
00:03:26,497 --> 00:03:29,459
I'm all right. No need to fret.

22
00:03:34,255 --> 00:03:38,134
{\an8}<i>As you can see,
smoke is still rising from the forest</i>

23
00:03:38,134 --> 00:03:41,971
<i>a full two days later
as scattered fires continue to burn.</i>

24
00:03:42,472 --> 00:03:45,934
<i>According to on-site investigators,
the legendary robot</i>

25
00:03:45,934 --> 00:03:49,646
<i>assigned to the Swiss Forestry Service,
Mont Blanc himself,</i>

26
00:03:49,646 --> 00:03:53,024
<i>was found dismembered
within the blaze's ring of destruction.</i>

27
00:03:53,942 --> 00:03:57,528
{\an8}<i>Mont Blanc was known the world over
as a mountain guide without equal.</i>

28
00:03:58,529 --> 00:04:01,741
{\an8}<i>He was a friend to children
and experienced climbers alike.</i>

29
00:04:02,408 --> 00:04:07,038
<i>The robot was also a tireless advocate
for man's better stewardship of nature.</i>

30
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:12,752
<i>Condolences for the beloved Mont Blanc
are pouring in from all over the globe.</i>

31
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:21,719
Yes, this is Gesicht.

32
00:04:23,888 --> 00:04:27,058
Yes. Understood. I'll be right there.

33
00:04:28,518 --> 00:04:30,353
Work call. I have to go.

34
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:32,313
Uh, but what about your breakfast?

35
00:04:43,616 --> 00:04:44,951
- Helena.
- Uh...

36
00:04:44,951 --> 00:04:46,703
Maybe I'll take some time off.

37
00:04:46,703 --> 00:04:48,621
- We could go on a trip.
- Huh?

38
00:04:49,414 --> 00:04:51,582
I should be getting more rest,
don't you think?

39
00:04:52,792 --> 00:04:55,545
You're right, but I never thought
I'd hear you say it.

40
00:05:16,065 --> 00:05:19,694
Bernard Lanke, 42 years old,
killed in his apartment.

41
00:05:20,194 --> 00:05:22,864
Big advocate
for the International Robot Laws.

42
00:05:25,283 --> 00:05:26,492
Was he a human?

43
00:05:26,492 --> 00:05:28,244
Oh. Uh, yes.

44
00:05:31,956 --> 00:05:34,876
Bad way to go. Just look at him.

45
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:37,086
Hmm?

46
00:05:41,132 --> 00:05:42,759
Hey! You there!

47
00:05:44,052 --> 00:05:46,637
You can stop rooting
through my crime scene anytime.

48
00:05:46,637 --> 00:05:50,391
Actually, sir, we've been expecting him.
He's Europol's guy.

49
00:05:50,391 --> 00:05:51,559
Hmm?

50
00:05:54,604 --> 00:05:56,272
Gesicht.

51
00:05:56,272 --> 00:05:58,566
Sorry for snapping at you like that.

52
00:05:58,566 --> 00:06:02,070
I'm Inspector Wallace
with the city police. A pleasure.

53
00:06:02,070 --> 00:06:04,989
I'm sure you've noticed,
but our killer wrecked the place.

54
00:06:04,989 --> 00:06:07,784
We're trying to figure out
if anything was stolen during the attack,

55
00:06:07,784 --> 00:06:09,994
but, uh, it's gonna take us some time.

56
00:06:09,994 --> 00:06:13,456
No, I don't think robbery
was a factor at play here.

57
00:06:13,456 --> 00:06:15,666
Huh? How do you figure?

58
00:06:16,250 --> 00:06:17,919
No sign of a search.

59
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:20,421
Come on!
With this much damage, who can say?

60
00:06:20,421 --> 00:06:21,964
I can tell.

61
00:06:21,964 --> 00:06:24,133
This damage is from the attack itself.

62
00:06:26,677 --> 00:06:29,389
All right. Then tell me
what you make of this.

63
00:06:41,984 --> 00:06:44,862
Why'd they go to the trouble
of jamming stuff into his head

64
00:06:44,862 --> 00:06:46,864
like a pair of damn horns?

65
00:06:46,864 --> 00:06:48,699
Hmm?

66
00:06:49,367 --> 00:06:50,618
Yes. Go ahead.

67
00:06:51,619 --> 00:06:53,204
Hold on. They what?

68
00:06:55,456 --> 00:06:57,542
They're saying someone attacked
one of our checkpoints!

69
00:07:13,015 --> 00:07:14,600
We need medevac! ASAP!

70
00:07:18,688 --> 00:07:21,274
Did the perp attack
anybody else, constable?

71
00:07:21,816 --> 00:07:26,112
Robby, sir.
He was at the checkpoint with me.

72
00:07:26,863 --> 00:07:28,114
He's my partner.

73
00:07:29,115 --> 00:07:31,742
Like, a constable-bot, you know?

74
00:07:31,742 --> 00:07:34,245
Model PRC1332.

75
00:07:42,253 --> 00:07:46,257
Hard to believe that a police robot
could be destroyed so easily.

76
00:07:48,676 --> 00:07:49,927
Inspector!

77
00:07:50,636 --> 00:07:53,890
We got word of a male fleeing toward
the old city's redevelopment zone.

78
00:07:53,890 --> 00:07:55,224
He matches our perp.

79
00:07:55,224 --> 00:07:58,728
Twenties, wearing a red cap,
and tattoos on both arms.

80
00:07:58,728 --> 00:08:01,189
Well, then?
Pair up and search the place!

81
00:08:01,189 --> 00:08:02,231
Huh?

82
00:08:02,231 --> 00:08:05,276
Hey! I said, "Pair up,"
you damn show-off!

83
00:08:06,277 --> 00:08:07,111
Oh!

84
00:08:07,653 --> 00:08:10,198
Damn it! Europol can kiss my ass!

85
00:09:23,729 --> 00:09:25,231
I suggest you calm down.

86
00:09:25,231 --> 00:09:26,607
I didn't do anything!

87
00:09:26,607 --> 00:09:29,360
That steel pipe you're holding
has traces of material

88
00:09:29,360 --> 00:09:31,070
from a destroyed constable-bot.

89
00:09:33,239 --> 00:09:37,034
Ah. You're an addict
high on a drug called "noi."

90
00:09:37,034 --> 00:09:39,161
Taken about 40 minutes ago.

91
00:09:39,161 --> 00:09:40,204
Sound about right?

92
00:09:41,914 --> 00:09:44,250
This is the part where you tell me
who you bought it from.

93
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:49,255
A guy on Karl-Heinz Street.
I only know him as Shultz, okay?

94
00:09:49,255 --> 00:09:51,465
And when
did you last see Shultz?

95
00:09:52,216 --> 00:09:54,218
Uh, early this morning before 5:00.

96
00:09:54,218 --> 00:09:57,638
If the dealer's version of events
happens to line up with what you said,

97
00:09:57,638 --> 00:09:59,140
then you have an alibi.

98
00:10:00,308 --> 00:10:03,686
5:00 a.m. is around the time
that Bernard Lanke was murdered.

99
00:10:03,686 --> 00:10:05,813
Mu... murdered? What the--

100
00:10:05,813 --> 00:10:08,983
If I had to guess,
you attacked the officer with that pipe

101
00:10:08,983 --> 00:10:11,402
to avoid getting collared
on a drug charge.

102
00:10:12,028 --> 00:10:15,698
After him,
you destroyed a local constable-bot.

103
00:10:16,282 --> 00:10:18,784
Now, I can read you your rights
and arrest you without incident,

104
00:10:18,784 --> 00:10:19,869
or we can do this--

105
00:10:31,047 --> 00:10:32,757
Don't shoot me! Come on, man!

106
00:10:32,757 --> 00:10:34,008
You're perfectly safe.

107
00:10:34,008 --> 00:10:36,927
This gun's only equipped
to fire non-lethal sleeping gas.

108
00:10:37,511 --> 00:10:39,930
My construction forbids
the killing of a human.

109
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:41,807
{\an8}Like your victim,

110
00:10:41,807 --> 00:10:43,184
{\an8}I'm a robot too.

111
00:10:51,692 --> 00:10:53,444
<i>Yes? Who is it?</i>

112
00:10:53,944 --> 00:10:57,573
I'm Gesicht, ma'am. A detective.
I'm here on behalf of Europol.

113
00:10:59,867 --> 00:11:01,660
Can I help you?

114
00:11:01,660 --> 00:11:03,746
You are Robby's wife, correct?

115
00:11:03,746 --> 00:11:04,747
Yes.

116
00:11:05,790 --> 00:11:07,708
I'm afraid I have some bad news.

117
00:11:16,092 --> 00:11:17,802
Can I offer you
a cup of tea?

118
00:11:18,302 --> 00:11:19,720
You're a robot, same as me,

119
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:22,973
so I'm sure you'll just go through
the motions of drinking it.

120
00:11:23,974 --> 00:11:25,601
By living as the humans do,

121
00:11:25,601 --> 00:11:30,523
they say we robots can upgrade our senses
or refine them. Same difference, I guess.

122
00:11:31,649 --> 00:11:33,818
I suppose all that is true enough.

123
00:11:34,568 --> 00:11:38,322
But I still don't understand why
drinking tea is such a comfort to them.

124
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:41,784
Maybe it's too subtle
for an outdated model like me.

125
00:11:44,328 --> 00:11:48,499
I have a job.
I work as a maid for this one family.

126
00:11:48,499 --> 00:11:52,378
They have a child. A boy.
All of them humans, of course.

127
00:11:53,295 --> 00:11:57,049
The parents had adopted a dog
back before the child was even born.

128
00:11:57,633 --> 00:12:00,136
The boy and the dog grew up like siblings.

129
00:12:00,970 --> 00:12:03,973
But then, one day, the dog died.

130
00:12:09,061 --> 00:12:14,024
Would it help if I were to erase
a portion of your memory data?

131
00:12:15,609 --> 00:12:18,863
My memories of him?
Please don't.

132
00:12:25,453 --> 00:12:28,247
Whole thing's a damn mess.

133
00:12:28,247 --> 00:12:31,417
The murder victim here
is one Bernard Lanke.

134
00:12:31,417 --> 00:12:33,961
The key member
of a Robot Law advocacy group.

135
00:12:33,961 --> 00:12:35,588
So I see.

136
00:12:36,130 --> 00:12:37,840
I'm sure there are
plenty of people out there

137
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:41,677
with no love for a scholar
who pushed so hard for robot rights.

138
00:12:41,677 --> 00:12:44,680
The body was found
in the following condition.

139
00:12:48,058 --> 00:12:50,394
That supposed to be horns
coming out of his head or what?

140
00:12:50,394 --> 00:12:52,897
I'm not sure.

141
00:12:52,897 --> 00:12:53,814
However...

142
00:13:00,946 --> 00:13:03,824
- Huh?
- Huh? Don't tell me that's--

143
00:13:04,408 --> 00:13:06,452
This is how
they found Mont Blanc

144
00:13:06,452 --> 00:13:08,287
right after he was destroyed.

145
00:13:08,287 --> 00:13:09,538
More horns.

146
00:13:09,538 --> 00:13:10,456
Wait a minute!

147
00:13:10,456 --> 00:13:14,001
Are you saying that whoever tore
Mont Blanc to pieces also killed Lanke?

148
00:13:15,002 --> 00:13:18,881
Inflicting that level of damage
upon a robot as sturdy as Mont Blanc

149
00:13:18,881 --> 00:13:21,091
is beyond human capability.

150
00:13:21,091 --> 00:13:25,763
Also, Lanke was the only human
in his apartment at the time of his death.

151
00:13:25,763 --> 00:13:29,266
I scanned the murder scene myself
and found no other traces.

152
00:13:29,266 --> 00:13:30,935
He was the only human in there?

153
00:13:30,935 --> 00:13:32,895
So what the hell are you suggesting?

154
00:13:32,895 --> 00:13:34,813
You know where I'm going with this.

155
00:13:34,813 --> 00:13:35,814
I do.

156
00:13:35,814 --> 00:13:38,818
The International Robot Laws, Article 13.

157
00:13:38,818 --> 00:13:41,403
No robot can harm or murder a human.

158
00:13:41,403 --> 00:13:43,614
But if... if there's a robot out there

159
00:13:43,614 --> 00:13:46,492
who's found a way
to murder human beings at will,

160
00:13:47,159 --> 00:13:50,079
then we're right back
where we were eight years ago.

161
00:13:56,168 --> 00:13:58,128
I'll track down
our perpetrator, sir.

162
00:13:58,128 --> 00:14:00,130
Whether our killer is human or robot,

163
00:14:00,130 --> 00:14:03,300
there's a devil inside them,
and it must be stopped.

164
00:14:10,391 --> 00:14:13,018
A strange pedestal, isn't it?

165
00:14:13,018 --> 00:14:14,103
Back in the day,

166
00:14:14,103 --> 00:14:18,983
there was talk of building a giant statue
of Mont Blanc and putting it on top.

167
00:14:18,983 --> 00:14:22,778
However, Mont Blanc let us know
he didn't much like the idea.

168
00:14:22,778 --> 00:14:26,323
He said it would be wrong
to ruin such a scenic view of the Alps

169
00:14:26,323 --> 00:14:28,576
with a needless monument like that.

170
00:14:29,785 --> 00:14:33,747
He didn't even want us to hang onto
his body once he was nonfunctional.

171
00:14:34,498 --> 00:14:37,084
"Break it up, melt it down, recycle it."

172
00:14:37,084 --> 00:14:40,004
"No point hanging onto an empty husk,"
he would say.

173
00:14:40,546 --> 00:14:44,675
I keep thinking back
to when he was still in his prime.

174
00:14:44,675 --> 00:14:48,637
<i>Mont Blanc was a hero
in the truest sense of the word.</i>

175
00:14:50,055 --> 00:14:52,474
<i>He served in the 39th Central Asian War</i>

176
00:14:52,474 --> 00:14:54,894
<i>as a key member
of the peace-keeping forces.</i>

177
00:14:56,145 --> 00:14:59,106
<i>Not only did he help restore peace
in the Kingdom of Persia</i>

178
00:14:59,106 --> 00:15:00,858
<i>after the turmoil of war,</i>

179
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:05,070
<i>but he apprehended many terrorist cells
without any bloodshed.</i>

180
00:15:05,654 --> 00:15:07,114
<i>Without Mont Blanc,</i>

181
00:15:07,114 --> 00:15:10,284
<i>Asia could never have achieved
its current state of peace.</i>

182
00:15:11,619 --> 00:15:13,829
<i>He was a poet and a friend of nature.</i>

183
00:15:14,371 --> 00:15:18,334
<i>He enjoyed singing with the birds
and talking with the trees of the forest.</i>

184
00:15:19,418 --> 00:15:22,087
See those people
setting up his memorial?

185
00:15:22,087 --> 00:15:26,467
Volunteers, every single one,
because they loved him.

186
00:15:27,051 --> 00:15:30,429
They loved my son
from the bottom of their hearts.

187
00:15:31,430 --> 00:15:35,142
<i>Mont Blanc.
Guardian angel of the Alps.</i>

188
00:15:35,142 --> 00:15:38,187
Tens-- No, hundreds of thousands
will come.

189
00:15:38,187 --> 00:15:41,190
They'll flock to this memorial
in three days' time...

190
00:15:41,190 --> 00:15:43,901
here to grieve the passing of their hero.

191
00:15:43,901 --> 00:15:47,863
Look, Detective,
Mont Blanc's death was no accident.

192
00:15:49,406 --> 00:15:52,326
They say it was a freak tornado
that destroyed him.

193
00:15:52,326 --> 00:15:54,870
And one was reported
in the area that night

194
00:15:54,870 --> 00:15:57,790
mere moments before the fire
that burned the forest,

195
00:15:57,790 --> 00:15:59,458
but that's not what killed him.

196
00:16:00,042 --> 00:16:03,420
I beg of you.
Catch whoever did this to my boy.

197
00:16:04,004 --> 00:16:08,133
Find them, and I'll beat them bloody
with my own hands!

198
00:16:08,842 --> 00:16:12,513
<i>As the pride
of Switzerland and the world at large,</i>

199
00:16:12,513 --> 00:16:14,848
<i>Mont Blanc will live on forever...</i>

200
00:16:14,848 --> 00:16:17,351
<i>...cherished in the memories
of all who knew him.</i>

201
00:16:34,410 --> 00:16:37,246
<i>Are you awake, Gesicht?
Rise and shine.</i>

202
00:16:37,996 --> 00:16:40,165
<i>That'll do it for your
scheduled maintenance today.</i>

203
00:16:40,165 --> 00:16:43,711
You have my thanks, Professor Hoffman.
So, everything normal?

204
00:16:43,711 --> 00:16:46,755
<i>Yes. There's nothing out of the ordinary.</i>

205
00:16:46,755 --> 00:16:47,673
<i>Except...</i>

206
00:16:48,257 --> 00:16:49,174
Go on.

207
00:16:49,758 --> 00:16:53,095
<i>Well, most people assume
robots aren't capable of getting tired,</i>

208
00:16:53,095 --> 00:16:55,723
<i>but given how human you are
in your design,</i>

209
00:16:55,723 --> 00:16:57,391
<i>fatigue is a real possibility.</i>

210
00:16:57,391 --> 00:16:58,851
And why not?

211
00:16:58,851 --> 00:17:01,937
The human body is just a mechanism,
the same as you are.

212
00:17:01,937 --> 00:17:06,150
No mechanism, flesh or otherwise,
can avoid the perils of overwork.

213
00:17:06,150 --> 00:17:07,359
Overwork?

214
00:17:08,610 --> 00:17:12,114
You've got a difficult caseload
at the moment. No doubt about that.

215
00:17:12,114 --> 00:17:14,241
I tried to watch Mont Blanc's memorial,

216
00:17:14,241 --> 00:17:18,579
but I ended up turning it off
after a while to keep myself from crying.

217
00:17:19,663 --> 00:17:21,248
There's a theory that some sort of

218
00:17:21,248 --> 00:17:25,044
internal electromagnetic wave anomaly
made him self-destruct.

219
00:17:25,627 --> 00:17:28,088
But as an expert on the subject,

220
00:17:28,088 --> 00:17:30,883
I don't believe a marvel of engineering
like Mont Blanc

221
00:17:30,883 --> 00:17:34,178
could ever be taken out
by such a minor error as that.

222
00:17:35,804 --> 00:17:40,392
Destroying a robot whom everyone adored.
Do you think you can find the perpetrator?

223
00:17:43,437 --> 00:17:46,065
I'm sure that mystery
is going to prove a challenge.

224
00:17:46,940 --> 00:17:49,818
At the same time, though,
that other case you're on,

225
00:17:49,818 --> 00:17:51,695
it looks complicated too.

226
00:17:51,695 --> 00:17:53,864
The murder of Bernard Lanke.

227
00:17:53,864 --> 00:17:56,992
I watched him advocate
for robot rights on TV many a time.

228
00:17:56,992 --> 00:17:59,328
No surprise he fell afoul of someone.

229
00:18:00,037 --> 00:18:02,456
Sure, the man had a right
to defend his opinions,

230
00:18:02,456 --> 00:18:04,291
but his remarks could cut like a knife.

231
00:18:04,875 --> 00:18:07,127
He always had
an air of condescension about him.

232
00:18:07,127 --> 00:18:09,171
Not a good way to make any friends.

233
00:18:09,171 --> 00:18:12,174
If you think about it,
they're the opposite of each other.

234
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:14,593
A robot and a human being.

235
00:18:14,593 --> 00:18:17,846
One of them had no enemies,
and the other had nothing but.

236
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:21,225
Yeah, juggling two tough cases like that
at the same time?

237
00:18:21,225 --> 00:18:23,018
That would tire out anybody.

238
00:18:24,186 --> 00:18:26,939
Do you mind
if I ask you something, Professor?

239
00:18:26,939 --> 00:18:28,273
Not at all.

240
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:31,568
Can a human enter a room
and then commit a crime there

241
00:18:31,568 --> 00:18:33,987
without leaving
any sort of biological trace?

242
00:18:34,822 --> 00:18:36,907
In other words, organic traces so minute,

243
00:18:36,907 --> 00:18:39,368
they can't be detected
by your sensor loadout.

244
00:18:39,368 --> 00:18:41,829
- Is that what you're asking me?
- Yes.

245
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:44,581
Uh-huh. Quite the hypothetical.

246
00:18:44,581 --> 00:18:46,708
That is gonna take some thought.

247
00:18:50,420 --> 00:18:52,631
Call it my homework for next time.

248
00:18:52,631 --> 00:18:54,216
Oh, what am I saying?

249
00:18:54,216 --> 00:18:56,260
These checkups
should be your break from work.

250
00:18:56,844 --> 00:18:58,595
No more shoptalk, all right?

251
00:19:04,101 --> 00:19:06,812
Incidentally, I brought up the idea
with my wife

252
00:19:06,812 --> 00:19:09,106
of us maybe going on a little trip.

253
00:19:09,106 --> 00:19:10,732
Well, that sounds nice.

254
00:19:10,732 --> 00:19:12,651
But she has her work to think of as well,

255
00:19:12,651 --> 00:19:14,945
so who can say
when we'll get around to it.

256
00:19:14,945 --> 00:19:16,697
Traveling is healthy.

257
00:19:16,697 --> 00:19:18,699
The data is unanimous.

258
00:19:18,699 --> 00:19:20,784
Seeing more of the world
is a great experience

259
00:19:20,784 --> 00:19:22,661
for an artificial intelligence.

260
00:19:22,661 --> 00:19:25,205
You should go somewhere
completely different, like Japan!

261
00:19:25,789 --> 00:19:26,915
Japan?

262
00:19:26,915 --> 00:19:27,833
Uh-huh!

263
00:19:27,833 --> 00:19:30,752
A member of their scientific community
invited me over there once,

264
00:19:30,752 --> 00:19:32,546
and I jumped at the chance to visit.

265
00:19:32,546 --> 00:19:35,757
Tokyo is so interesting.
So much to see and do!

266
00:19:35,757 --> 00:19:38,969
Sounds like fun.
I'll run the idea past my wife.

267
00:19:39,678 --> 00:19:41,513
Hope you don't mind my asking,

268
00:19:41,513 --> 00:19:44,558
but are you still having
that dream you told me about?

269
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:48,729
I am.

270
00:19:48,729 --> 00:19:50,689
Oh! Not that I'm trying
to pry it out of you.

271
00:19:50,689 --> 00:19:52,149
That would be rude of me.

272
00:19:52,149 --> 00:19:55,611
But I am intrigued at the thought
of artificial minds having dreams.

273
00:19:56,320 --> 00:19:59,406
At this point, it's pretty well-accepted
within the scientific community

274
00:19:59,406 --> 00:20:02,701
that artificial intelligence
includes a subconscious element.

275
00:20:02,701 --> 00:20:07,080
Still, it's rare to encounter a robot that
has any waking memory of the dream state.

276
00:20:07,664 --> 00:20:10,626
When you feel up to it,
could you maybe tell me what you've seen?

277
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:11,543
Hmm.

278
00:20:11,543 --> 00:20:14,713
As the 20th-century psychiatrist
Sigmund Freud was known

279
00:20:14,713 --> 00:20:16,298
to occasionally say,

280
00:20:16,298 --> 00:20:19,635
"Our dreams are more than just
idle flights of the imagination."

281
00:20:19,635 --> 00:20:22,012
"Dreams are expressions of our reality."

282
00:20:40,948 --> 00:20:43,116
- Excuse me, sir.
- Hmm?

283
00:20:47,246 --> 00:20:49,873
Is that a constable-bot?

284
00:20:49,873 --> 00:20:51,708
Uh-huh. Says it right there.

285
00:20:52,417 --> 00:20:55,671
Cops are done doing forensics,
so it's time to junk it.

286
00:20:56,922 --> 00:20:58,048
You're Robby.

287
00:20:58,757 --> 00:20:59,675
Hmm?

288
00:21:00,717 --> 00:21:03,595
Would you mind
if I take a quick look at him?

289
00:21:04,096 --> 00:21:05,806
Yeah, sure. Go ahead.

290
00:21:05,806 --> 00:21:08,267
If there's any parts you want,
take 'em with you.

291
00:21:08,267 --> 00:21:09,601
The body's scrap at this point.

292
00:21:14,064 --> 00:21:16,858
500 Zeus a body.
What do you say?

293
00:21:18,902 --> 00:21:19,945
What's the matter?

294
00:21:24,741 --> 00:21:27,286
Uh, it's nothing. Nothing at all.

295
00:21:29,037 --> 00:21:30,497
Zoned out for a second.

296
00:21:35,085 --> 00:21:37,170
This is
your husband's memory chip.

297
00:21:38,672 --> 00:21:41,758
Not to overstep,
but I thought you might want it.

298
00:21:42,676 --> 00:21:47,597
Oh my goodness.
This means so much to me. Thank you.

299
00:21:47,597 --> 00:21:50,017
Well then, I can see myself out.

300
00:21:51,727 --> 00:21:52,728
Wait!

301
00:21:53,312 --> 00:21:56,523
Could I trouble you to insert it, please?

302
00:21:57,899 --> 00:22:00,235
There could be painful memories on there.

303
00:22:07,492 --> 00:22:10,537
The overlapping sets of memories
could cause a malfunction.

304
00:22:10,537 --> 00:22:12,873
If that happens,
I'm ejecting it right away.

305
00:22:15,125 --> 00:22:17,836
My Robby.
He's here with me.

306
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:32,100
Huh?

307
00:22:32,684 --> 00:22:34,561
Ma'am, that's enough! I'm taking it out!

308
00:22:34,561 --> 00:22:38,607
His final memories are clearly
too traumatic for you! I'm ejecting it!

309
00:22:39,441 --> 00:22:41,526
- That's strange.
- Huh?

310
00:22:42,652 --> 00:22:44,279
What could it be?

311
00:22:45,489 --> 00:22:48,075
- What do you see, ma'am?
- I'll display it.

312
00:22:57,709 --> 00:23:02,089
Footage of Robby's partner stopping a car
at their checkpoint before the attack.

313
00:23:07,677 --> 00:23:09,554
He takes out the human cop.

314
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:19,689
Please forgive me.

315
00:23:20,273 --> 00:23:22,818
Seeing that firsthand
must have been traumatic.

316
00:23:23,443 --> 00:23:25,362
I can't apologize enough.

317
00:23:25,362 --> 00:23:26,905
- It's not that.
- Hmm?

318
00:23:27,531 --> 00:23:31,493
My husband, he reacted
to the sight of the steel pipe at once.

319
00:23:31,993 --> 00:23:34,538
I could see his stun gun at the ready.

320
00:23:34,538 --> 00:23:35,789
I saw that.

321
00:23:35,789 --> 00:23:38,083
It's very unusual that a human perpetrator

322
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:40,794
can mount a successful attack
on a constable-bot.

323
00:23:41,294 --> 00:23:43,255
There's a lot we still don't understand
about how--

324
00:23:43,255 --> 00:23:44,714
- I know why.
- Hmm?

325
00:23:44,714 --> 00:23:46,383
Watch the moment again.

326
00:23:49,428 --> 00:23:52,806
With this chip in me,
I can track the memory frame by frame.

327
00:23:53,515 --> 00:23:55,767
It starts when he hits Robby's partner.

328
00:23:56,351 --> 00:23:57,811
Up until this moment,

329
00:23:57,811 --> 00:24:00,814
my husband never takes his eyes off
the man with the pipe.

330
00:24:01,481 --> 00:24:03,525
But as the man rushes him,

331
00:24:04,192 --> 00:24:06,987
he was distracted by something.

332
00:24:07,487 --> 00:24:08,905
There, behind him!

333
00:24:08,905 --> 00:24:11,408
That was the apartment
Lanke was murdered in!

334
00:24:14,452 --> 00:24:16,079
That shot, right there!

335
00:24:18,165 --> 00:24:20,750
- What is that thing?
- I can zoom in some.

336
00:24:23,628 --> 00:24:25,589
Definitely not a bird.

337
00:24:25,589 --> 00:24:27,340
Forensics went over all the footage,

338
00:24:27,340 --> 00:24:29,676
so why was there no mention made
of this shot?

339
00:24:30,177 --> 00:24:32,596
Unless you had
the memory chip inserted,

340
00:24:32,596 --> 00:24:35,015
you'd never notice something so brief.

341
00:24:35,015 --> 00:24:39,519
My husband caught sight of this silhouette
and was able to analyze it

342
00:24:39,519 --> 00:24:41,980
during the fraction of a second
it was in view.

343
00:24:41,980 --> 00:24:43,607
It can't be a human.

344
00:24:43,607 --> 00:24:46,276
Not the way it's jumping
from one building to another.

345
00:24:46,276 --> 00:24:49,029
Yes. But, Detective...

346
00:24:49,529 --> 00:24:50,530
Huh?

347
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:52,908
...that's not a robot.

348
00:25:06,963 --> 00:25:10,842
<i>A murder in a room
with no trace of a human assailant.</i>

349
00:25:12,219 --> 00:25:15,180
<i>The death of a robot,
loved the world over.</i>

350
00:25:17,015 --> 00:25:18,683
<i>And horns.</i>

351
00:25:36,535 --> 00:25:38,662
<i>Identity confirmed.</i>

352
00:25:38,662 --> 00:25:40,163
<i>Please step forward.</i>

353
00:26:10,777 --> 00:26:13,697
Says you're a robot.
That true or what, Detective?

354
00:26:13,697 --> 00:26:14,614
Yes.

355
00:26:14,614 --> 00:26:17,158
Well, you could've fooled me
with that face.

356
00:26:19,744 --> 00:26:22,330
The electromagnetic waves he emits
are pretty strong.

357
00:26:22,330 --> 00:26:25,083
They could scramble your AI
if you get too close to him.

358
00:26:25,083 --> 00:26:27,377
Wear this to keep you safe.

359
00:26:27,377 --> 00:26:28,753
I'm okay, thanks.

360
00:26:28,753 --> 00:26:31,423
I'm immune. They have no effect on me.

361
00:26:31,423 --> 00:26:32,340
Really?

362
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:35,218
A very special alloy
was used in my construction.

363
00:26:35,218 --> 00:26:36,553
I'm plain on the outside though.

364
00:26:37,137 --> 00:26:40,932
All right. Your call, sir,
but stay on your guard.

365
00:26:42,392 --> 00:26:43,893
In the time he's been here,

366
00:26:43,893 --> 00:26:47,188
he's taken out four robots
who tried to engage with him.

367
00:27:09,377 --> 00:27:11,004
Like the barricade?

368
00:27:11,004 --> 00:27:13,757
It would be funny
if it weren't so desperate.

369
00:27:14,341 --> 00:27:15,675
They fear me.

370
00:27:15,675 --> 00:27:18,094
The humans threw together
that pile of junk

371
00:27:18,094 --> 00:27:21,222
so they can pretend
they're not quaking in their boots.

372
00:27:26,478 --> 00:27:29,356
So you're Brau1589.

373
00:27:36,988 --> 00:27:42,869
Robot Model HRS0288,
Inspector Gesicht.

374
00:27:42,869 --> 00:27:46,623
In terms of detective AI,
you're the best there is.

375
00:27:46,623 --> 00:27:49,834
If you can discern my model,
your ID function still works.

376
00:27:49,834 --> 00:27:52,003
Ah, you're sleuthing already.

377
00:27:52,003 --> 00:27:55,340
If anything,
it's more powerful than before.

378
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:58,259
Locked away
and smashed half to hell as I am,

379
00:27:58,259 --> 00:28:02,806
I can't help but be curious
about what's happening in the world above.

380
00:28:03,515 --> 00:28:06,518
I came here today because
there's something I needed to ask you.

381
00:28:06,518 --> 00:28:08,019
Let me guess.

382
00:28:08,019 --> 00:28:10,480
What went through the mind
of a certain robot

383
00:28:10,480 --> 00:28:14,067
when it murdered a human
eight years ago, right?

384
00:28:17,112 --> 00:28:20,699
Robot rights scholar
Bernard Lanke was killed at home.

385
00:28:21,199 --> 00:28:22,450
I scanned the murder scene,

386
00:28:22,450 --> 00:28:25,203
but there were no traces
of another human there.

387
00:28:25,829 --> 00:28:28,081
So was the killer a human, or was it--

388
00:28:28,081 --> 00:28:29,833
Or was it a robot?

389
00:28:29,833 --> 00:28:32,919
And if it was a robot,
why'd it do such a thing?

390
00:28:33,586 --> 00:28:37,882
Just between us,
the humans examined every last bit of it.

391
00:28:37,882 --> 00:28:41,469
My murderous artificial intelligence
that is.

392
00:28:41,469 --> 00:28:44,681
They were so sure
that a defect was to blame.

393
00:28:44,681 --> 00:28:45,807
But, no.

394
00:28:45,807 --> 00:28:48,351
They couldn't find
a single thing wrong with me.

395
00:28:48,351 --> 00:28:53,314
My AI passed the tests with flying colors.
No flaw in sight.

396
00:28:55,358 --> 00:28:59,571
Can you imagine how terrified
the humans were when they found that out?

397
00:28:59,571 --> 00:29:03,992
That's why they keep me locked away
down here, skewered and broken.

398
00:29:03,992 --> 00:29:06,745
If they're that afraid,
they should just pull out this spear.

399
00:29:06,745 --> 00:29:08,329
That would kill me dead.

400
00:29:08,329 --> 00:29:12,500
But, alas, my human captors
are too spineless even for that.

401
00:29:16,296 --> 00:29:19,257
Inspector Gesicht, if you want to peek

402
00:29:19,257 --> 00:29:21,509
into the head of a robot
who's committed murder,

403
00:29:21,509 --> 00:29:25,263
all you have to do is
exchange memory chips with me.

404
00:29:25,263 --> 00:29:28,725
Who knows?
You might learn all sorts of things.

405
00:29:39,319 --> 00:29:42,238
Those are some printed images
of Mont Blanc's destruction

406
00:29:42,238 --> 00:29:43,990
and the Lanke murder scene.

407
00:29:44,741 --> 00:29:47,702
The horns in both of them.
What could they mean?

408
00:29:48,787 --> 00:29:51,331
The ancient gods of Europe
come to mind.

409
00:29:51,831 --> 00:29:55,418
The god of death. He had horns like these.

410
00:29:55,418 --> 00:29:59,255
There was Herne the Hunter,
who took the souls of warriors.

411
00:29:59,255 --> 00:30:01,841
He was called the "Horned King."

412
00:30:01,841 --> 00:30:03,092
In Greek mythology,

413
00:30:03,092 --> 00:30:06,721
the horned king of the underworld
was Hades, of course.

414
00:30:06,721 --> 00:30:09,390
The Roman god of the dead

415
00:30:09,390 --> 00:30:11,601
was Pluto.

416
00:30:13,603 --> 00:30:14,896
A god of the dead.

417
00:30:16,022 --> 00:30:19,275
Whoever did this,
they will strike again.

418
00:30:20,235 --> 00:30:23,613
Mont Blanc, one of
the most advanced robots on earth,

419
00:30:23,613 --> 00:30:26,825
was ripped apart
like he was a children's toy.

420
00:30:26,825 --> 00:30:30,245
Come on, Detective.
Do I need to spell it out for you?

421
00:30:30,245 --> 00:30:32,747
A handful of robots were created

422
00:30:32,747 --> 00:30:36,167
with the best technologies
the world had to offer.

423
00:30:36,167 --> 00:30:40,046
Robots who can also be
weapons of mass destruction.

424
00:30:40,547 --> 00:30:44,676
You already know who else is
in the crosshairs, do you not?

425
00:30:44,676 --> 00:30:48,638
There are six of them left,
present company included.

426
00:31:49,449 --> 00:31:50,867
I am trying to work.

427
00:31:50,867 --> 00:31:53,703
Don't just stand there in silence
like a damn mannequin.

428
00:31:54,871 --> 00:31:57,373
Sorry to have entered
without your permission.

429
00:31:57,874 --> 00:31:59,959
The security seems to have been disabled.

430
00:31:59,959 --> 00:32:01,669
Mm-hmm.

431
00:32:01,669 --> 00:32:05,381
Given your visual impairment,
that is not safe.

432
00:32:05,381 --> 00:32:09,761
No burglar's going to tromp out
to the middle of nowhere to steal from me.

433
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:13,640
- But Sir Duncan, you--
- Enough. Are you the new butler?

434
00:32:14,223 --> 00:32:15,183
Yes, sir.

435
00:32:15,183 --> 00:32:19,103
{\an8}I'm sure the agency sent me over
another good-for-nothing.

436
00:32:19,103 --> 00:32:20,146
{\an8}You got a name?

437
00:32:20,146 --> 00:32:23,650
Yes, sir.
You can refer to me as North No.2.

438
00:32:24,192 --> 00:32:26,861
{\an8}Direction and a number. Riveting.

439
00:32:28,738 --> 00:32:32,241
The staffing agency told me
you have a military background.

440
00:32:32,241 --> 00:32:34,786
Do you care to elaborate on that?

441
00:32:34,786 --> 00:32:37,580
Yes, sir.
I previously served as a butler

442
00:32:37,580 --> 00:32:39,624
for the Commander-in-Chief
of the British Army

443
00:32:39,624 --> 00:32:42,543
for the entirety
of the 39th Central Asian War.

444
00:32:42,543 --> 00:32:44,921
Hmm. Butler for a soldier, eh?

445
00:32:45,546 --> 00:32:48,216
I don't imagine
you're much to look at, are you?

446
00:32:48,716 --> 00:32:51,719
I wear a cape
while in the presence of others.

447
00:32:51,719 --> 00:32:55,515
But of course.
Your whole damn body's a weapon.

448
00:32:56,265 --> 00:32:58,977
- Make me tea, weapon.
- At once, sir.

449
00:32:59,644 --> 00:33:01,229
As for the type...

450
00:33:01,229 --> 00:33:02,647
Don't worry, sir.

451
00:33:02,647 --> 00:33:05,942
I made sure to download
all of your relevant data en route.

452
00:33:08,778 --> 00:33:12,407
What the hell's my "relevant data"?

453
00:33:13,741 --> 00:33:15,326
Prior to this assignment,

454
00:33:15,326 --> 00:33:18,287
I had the chance
to watch one of the films you worked on.

455
00:33:18,913 --> 00:33:21,916
It was the movie
<i>The Queen on the Satellite Orbit,</i>

456
00:33:21,916 --> 00:33:23,042
and I was very moved

457
00:33:23,042 --> 00:33:26,546
by how the soundtrack served
to uplift the imagery.

458
00:33:26,546 --> 00:33:28,965
Is that part of your "relevant data"?

459
00:33:28,965 --> 00:33:31,801
No, sir. I was sincerely moved by it.

460
00:33:31,801 --> 00:33:35,054
That film has been out
for more than a decade now.

461
00:33:35,638 --> 00:33:36,764
Your tea.

462
00:33:37,807 --> 00:33:39,767
Used to call me the "blind genius"

463
00:33:39,767 --> 00:33:42,854
back when I was stacking up film awards
like cordwood.

464
00:33:42,854 --> 00:33:44,772
Every score I composed was a hit.

465
00:33:44,772 --> 00:33:47,275
I'm sure you have the more recent reviews

466
00:33:47,275 --> 00:33:50,153
rattling around
in that metal skull of yours.

467
00:33:50,820 --> 00:33:54,282
"The wellspring of Paul Duncan's talent
has run dry."

468
00:33:54,824 --> 00:33:55,908
End quote.

469
00:33:56,409 --> 00:33:57,702
The hell it has.

470
00:33:57,702 --> 00:34:01,581
I could still compose circles
around anyone if I had a mind to.

471
00:34:01,581 --> 00:34:03,916
How dare they just write me off?

472
00:34:03,916 --> 00:34:07,170
They would be on their feet,
applauding at my simplest leitmotif,

473
00:34:07,170 --> 00:34:10,923
then I'd squeeze their heart with my notes
and leave them in tears.

474
00:34:10,923 --> 00:34:14,260
It's not that I can't compose.
It's that I refuse to.

475
00:34:14,260 --> 00:34:17,138
Such trivial things hold no appeal for me.

476
00:34:17,138 --> 00:34:20,349
But, sir,
you were at the piano just now.

477
00:34:20,349 --> 00:34:23,061
It was a beautiful piece,
if I may be so bold.

478
00:34:24,395 --> 00:34:26,773
That one's not meant
for the celluloid brothel.

479
00:34:26,773 --> 00:34:31,110
It's a song I write only for myself.
The world can't lay claim to any of it.

480
00:34:35,531 --> 00:34:38,242
- This cup of tea is much like your name.
- Sir?

481
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:40,703
Utterly lacking flavor.

482
00:34:40,703 --> 00:34:44,332
"A beautiful piece," eh?
Don't make me laugh.

483
00:34:44,332 --> 00:34:49,670
A hunk of military hardware like you has
no right to judge the value of my art.

484
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:53,132
My apologies, sir.

485
00:35:25,832 --> 00:35:27,583
How many did you kill?

486
00:35:27,583 --> 00:35:28,626
Sir?

487
00:35:29,127 --> 00:35:32,380
How many people did you kill
in the Central Asian War?

488
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:34,590
I'm sure you can give me an exact number.

489
00:35:35,591 --> 00:35:40,263
The International Robot Laws forbid me
from harming any humans. I am incapable.

490
00:35:40,972 --> 00:35:43,724
So then, killed lots of robots,
in other words.

491
00:35:45,184 --> 00:35:47,019
What does that number come out to?

492
00:35:49,063 --> 00:35:51,274
Don't pretend as though you've lost count.

493
00:35:53,526 --> 00:35:54,569
Get out of here.

494
00:35:55,653 --> 00:35:58,948
Your demeanor's ruining
what little appetite I have.

495
00:35:59,740 --> 00:36:01,200
I will take my leave.

496
00:36:27,435 --> 00:36:30,980
What are you doing?
You leave my piano alone, you hear me?

497
00:36:32,523 --> 00:36:34,108
My apologies, sir.

498
00:36:35,026 --> 00:36:36,360
When composing music,

499
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:38,946
this instrument
is the only one you employ.

500
00:36:38,946 --> 00:36:40,740
Yes. What of it?

501
00:36:40,740 --> 00:36:44,410
But you have so much
cutting-edge equipment at your disposal.

502
00:36:45,786 --> 00:36:47,997
They're cutting-edge fakeries,
just like you.

503
00:36:48,706 --> 00:36:51,500
A fake violin right there
next to a fake trumpet.

504
00:36:52,084 --> 00:36:54,420
The whole damn orchestra, fake.

505
00:36:54,420 --> 00:36:58,215
Oh, dress 'em up all you want.
They're nothing more than machines.

506
00:36:59,634 --> 00:37:00,718
No, thank you.

507
00:37:00,718 --> 00:37:03,262
That's why I never had
artificial eyes put in.

508
00:37:03,262 --> 00:37:06,307
If I need a machine
to tell me what the world looks like,

509
00:37:06,307 --> 00:37:08,184
then I'd rather not see at all.

510
00:37:08,184 --> 00:37:10,019
Far better to live in the dark.

511
00:37:10,019 --> 00:37:14,482
{\an8}The only sights worth laying eyes on
already exist within my memory.

512
00:37:15,691 --> 00:37:17,944
"The sights worth laying eyes on."

513
00:37:18,611 --> 00:37:22,448
Visions of my childhood home
back when I still had my sight.

514
00:37:22,448 --> 00:37:25,618
During your youth, sir,
back in Bohemia.

515
00:37:26,244 --> 00:37:28,412
That another tidbit from your data?

516
00:37:28,412 --> 00:37:32,250
It's all worthless when it's just a list
within your processors.

517
00:37:32,792 --> 00:37:35,002
It was such a beautiful milieu.

518
00:37:35,503 --> 00:37:38,089
{\an8}The fields run riot with green.

519
00:37:38,589 --> 00:37:40,383
{\an8}The wind's caress.

520
00:37:40,383 --> 00:37:45,388
{\an8}And always the glow
of the gently setting sun.

521
00:37:48,224 --> 00:37:51,727
<i>I will turn them into music.
I must.</i>

522
00:39:07,636 --> 00:39:10,723
I told you not to touch my piano,
you great clod!

523
00:39:11,724 --> 00:39:13,768
Yes, you have my apologies.

524
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:16,604
Even if you played a song to perfection,

525
00:39:16,604 --> 00:39:20,107
the notes and chords
would all be as artificial as you are.

526
00:39:21,108 --> 00:39:21,984
Sir Duncan.

527
00:39:21,984 --> 00:39:24,987
I do not mean to intrude
upon your privacy, sir,

528
00:39:24,987 --> 00:39:28,324
but I happened to notice that
you were moaning in your sleep last night.

529
00:39:28,324 --> 00:39:29,492
{\an8}Hmm?

530
00:39:29,492 --> 00:39:32,036
{\an8}However,
it sounded like you were humming

531
00:39:32,036 --> 00:39:33,704
{\an8}amidst the moans as well.

532
00:39:34,872 --> 00:39:35,998
I could be mistaken,

533
00:39:35,998 --> 00:39:39,001
but I think that melody,
born of your unconscious mind,

534
00:39:39,001 --> 00:39:42,254
is the missing portion of the song
you currently struggle to finish.

535
00:39:42,254 --> 00:39:45,341
It's the section where
you always stop midway.

536
00:39:47,301 --> 00:39:50,679
This is how it went, sir. More or less.

537
00:39:53,182 --> 00:39:54,683
Get out of here!

538
00:39:54,683 --> 00:39:57,895
{\an8}I have no need for you,
you piece of machinery!

539
00:39:57,895 --> 00:39:59,814
{\an8}Get out of my house this instant!

540
00:39:59,814 --> 00:40:01,232
But, sir--

541
00:40:01,232 --> 00:40:04,402
I am giving you an order! Leave at once!

542
00:40:06,654 --> 00:40:07,696
Sir Duncan.

543
00:40:11,117 --> 00:40:14,161
I would like to learn to play the piano
if you will teach me.

544
00:40:14,745 --> 00:40:16,622
What did you say?

545
00:40:16,622 --> 00:40:19,083
As you have told me numerous times,

546
00:40:19,083 --> 00:40:22,586
no matter how well I play,
it might always ring false.

547
00:40:23,254 --> 00:40:27,091
But I'd like to know
I got as close as I could.

548
00:40:27,091 --> 00:40:31,053
A weapon like you will never
play the piano, and that's final.

549
00:40:40,479 --> 00:40:41,397
Stop it!

550
00:40:41,397 --> 00:40:44,316
How dare you sully those keys,
you tool of war?

551
00:40:44,316 --> 00:40:47,403
{\an8}You belong on a battlefield,
and you know it!

552
00:40:48,654 --> 00:40:49,822
You are right.

553
00:40:51,907 --> 00:40:54,785
{\an8}That is why I'd like to learn
to play the piano.

554
00:40:55,911 --> 00:40:59,748
I do not want
to belong on the battlefield.

555
00:41:03,919 --> 00:41:05,671
Mother!

556
00:41:06,464 --> 00:41:07,631
Mother!

557
00:41:09,675 --> 00:41:12,052
No, please!

558
00:41:12,052 --> 00:41:13,304
Where are you?

559
00:41:19,059 --> 00:41:21,145
Wait for me!

560
00:41:23,898 --> 00:41:25,274
Whoa!

561
00:41:25,274 --> 00:41:28,277
Mother, don't leave me behind!
I'm right here!

562
00:41:29,945 --> 00:41:32,156
Mother!

563
00:41:33,407 --> 00:41:35,117
<i>Mother!</i>

564
00:41:40,164 --> 00:41:43,125
Are you there, North No.2?
I think that you are.

565
00:41:45,669 --> 00:41:49,048
I've told you before,
don't come into my bedroom.

566
00:41:49,048 --> 00:41:51,008
I apologize, Sir Duncan.

567
00:41:51,008 --> 00:41:53,844
I merely wanted to inform you
that breakfast is ready.

568
00:41:57,306 --> 00:41:59,266
I could've sworn I fired you.

569
00:42:02,144 --> 00:42:03,395
Are you still there?

570
00:42:13,280 --> 00:42:15,658
How many times must I say it?

571
00:42:18,494 --> 00:42:20,913
Don't you touch that piano! Not ever!

572
00:42:20,913 --> 00:42:23,916
Let me play for you. Please, Sir Duncan.

573
00:42:23,916 --> 00:42:26,377
I think I've gotten
a little better than before.

574
00:42:26,377 --> 00:42:28,545
"Gotten a little better," eh?

575
00:42:28,545 --> 00:42:33,259
The only improvement you can hope for is
if you turn yourself into a metronome!

576
00:42:34,218 --> 00:42:35,970
I will attempt to recreate the melody

577
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:38,389
you keep humming in your sleep,
Sir Duncan.

578
00:42:54,488 --> 00:42:58,325
The sounds you torture
out of that piano are not music!

579
00:43:01,078 --> 00:43:02,496
Damn this piece of junk!

580
00:43:03,289 --> 00:43:05,082
"Just input the data,

581
00:43:05,082 --> 00:43:08,669
and you can create infinite melodies
with the push of a button!"

582
00:43:11,630 --> 00:43:15,259
That's not music at all!
It's just sounds with no heart to it!

583
00:43:16,051 --> 00:43:18,345
You will break the machines
if you continue.

584
00:43:19,096 --> 00:43:22,224
Oh! Trying to protect
your own kind, is that it?

585
00:43:23,058 --> 00:43:24,393
I'll ask again.

586
00:43:24,393 --> 00:43:28,230
How many of your own kind
did you destroy on the battlefield?

587
00:43:29,815 --> 00:43:32,192
Take off the cape,
you cast-iron hypocrite!

588
00:43:32,192 --> 00:43:34,695
Show the world
your hideous weapon of a body!

589
00:43:34,695 --> 00:43:37,615
How many did you kill? Give me the number!

590
00:43:37,615 --> 00:43:40,117
How many notches carved into your side?

591
00:43:40,117 --> 00:43:42,870
Ha! You're a docile one, aren't you?

592
00:43:42,870 --> 00:43:44,705
A weapon of mass destruction

593
00:43:44,705 --> 00:43:48,542
programmed to behave
in front of his master, is that it?

594
00:43:50,002 --> 00:43:51,295
All right, then.

595
00:43:51,295 --> 00:43:53,380
I'm going to give you some data about me

596
00:43:53,380 --> 00:43:56,717
that I guarantee isn't rolling around
in that head of yours.

597
00:43:56,717 --> 00:44:00,012
It's the reason I moan in my sleep
in the dead of night.

598
00:44:00,596 --> 00:44:02,973
The nightmare I've had for years now.

599
00:44:04,058 --> 00:44:06,977
{\an8}Not a dream,
but the life that brought me to this.

600
00:44:06,977 --> 00:44:08,604
{\an8}Truth from long ago.

601
00:44:10,898 --> 00:44:13,525
<i>The world knows me
as Paul Duncan,</i>

602
00:44:13,525 --> 00:44:16,236
<i>but my real name is Paulo Holy.</i>

603
00:44:16,236 --> 00:44:19,156
<i>I was born into poverty in Bohemia.</i>

604
00:44:19,948 --> 00:44:21,659
<i>I can't remember my father.</i>

605
00:44:21,659 --> 00:44:23,661
<i>He died when I was young.</i>

606
00:44:23,661 --> 00:44:25,746
<i>I was born with a chronic illness.</i>

607
00:44:25,746 --> 00:44:29,833
<i>And even with thick glasses,
my eyesight was always poor.</i>

608
00:44:29,833 --> 00:44:32,628
<i>Singing songs was my only joy in life.</i>

609
00:44:33,754 --> 00:44:36,131
<i>My mother, she was a beauty.</i>

610
00:44:36,131 --> 00:44:37,675
<i>Even at her most threadbare,</i>

611
00:44:37,675 --> 00:44:41,095
<i>men would turn
and watch her walk down the street.</i>

612
00:44:41,720 --> 00:44:45,641
<i>One approached her.
He was a member of the nouveau-riche.</i>

613
00:44:46,392 --> 00:44:48,936
<i>And she, my mother,</i>

614
00:44:48,936 --> 00:44:52,272
<i>fell prey to a greed
that poisoned her heart.</i>

615
00:44:54,233 --> 00:44:55,359
Sick as I was,

616
00:44:55,359 --> 00:44:57,528
she must have thought me such a burden.

617
00:44:57,528 --> 00:44:59,571
Looking back, that has to be the reason

618
00:44:59,571 --> 00:45:01,240
why she did what she did.

619
00:45:02,324 --> 00:45:05,077
The reason why
she threw her own child away!

620
00:45:06,412 --> 00:45:10,958
<i>Out of nowhere, I was shipped off
to a boarding school in England.</i>

621
00:45:11,625 --> 00:45:13,252
<i>The other boys were cruel,</i>

622
00:45:13,752 --> 00:45:17,631
<i>and a weakling such as myself
was in no place to fight back.</i>

623
00:45:18,132 --> 00:45:19,591
<i>But through the worst of it,</i>

624
00:45:19,591 --> 00:45:23,554
<i>I clung to my music studies
like a drowning man.</i>

625
00:45:24,346 --> 00:45:26,515
<i>The long nights came at a price.</i>

626
00:45:26,515 --> 00:45:29,476
<i>I soon developed a fever I couldn't shake.</i>

627
00:45:29,476 --> 00:45:32,771
<i>Even my beloved music
slipped from my grasp.</i>

628
00:45:40,904 --> 00:45:44,408
<i>I was sent from hospital ward
to hospital ward,</i>

629
00:45:44,408 --> 00:45:47,077
<i>but every day saw me grow weaker.</i>

630
00:45:48,036 --> 00:45:49,872
<i>The doctors gave up on me.</i>

631
00:45:49,872 --> 00:45:52,624
<i>And through it all,
not a peep from my mother.</i>

632
00:45:54,585 --> 00:45:58,547
<i>I was dying. They knew it, and I did too.</i>

633
00:45:59,089 --> 00:46:01,884
<i>I would perish far from home,</i>

634
00:46:01,884 --> 00:46:03,969
<i>forgotten and forlorn.</i>

635
00:46:06,013 --> 00:46:09,391
<i>And that's when
a Japanese doctor walked into my room.</i>

636
00:46:09,391 --> 00:46:13,687
<i>He didn't have a license,
but lost causes were his specialty.</i>

637
00:46:15,022 --> 00:46:17,524
I'm going to save your life,
young man.

638
00:46:18,484 --> 00:46:22,404
But there's a chance
that you go blind in the bargain.

639
00:46:26,283 --> 00:46:28,285
<i>The surgery was a success.</i>

640
00:46:29,369 --> 00:46:33,415
<i>And yet,
just as the rogue doctor had predicted,</i>

641
00:46:33,415 --> 00:46:36,251
<i>my eyes grew weaker with each passing day.</i>

642
00:46:36,251 --> 00:46:38,170
<i>I knew time was running out,</i>

643
00:46:38,170 --> 00:46:41,089
<i>and there was
so much theory left to learn.</i>

644
00:46:41,089 --> 00:46:43,509
<i>I forsook everything but the music.</i>

645
00:46:44,218 --> 00:46:46,762
<i>Music was all I had left in the world.</i>

646
00:46:47,679 --> 00:46:50,057
<i>Play it again! Quickly, now!</i>

647
00:46:50,766 --> 00:46:54,561
<i>Not yet! Not yet! Not yet!</i>

648
00:46:58,357 --> 00:46:59,358
<i>And then,</i>

649
00:47:00,025 --> 00:47:02,277
<i>the darkness was complete.</i>

650
00:47:04,446 --> 00:47:07,783
A few years later,
I was told my mother had died.

651
00:47:08,283 --> 00:47:12,412
Her wealthy suitor never did bother
to make an honest woman out of her.

652
00:47:12,412 --> 00:47:15,791
They told me she was alone
when the end came.

653
00:47:15,791 --> 00:47:18,085
Abandoned, as I had been.

654
00:47:18,919 --> 00:47:20,379
I worked hard!

655
00:47:20,379 --> 00:47:24,424
When his fortunes fell,
I bought her lover's castle. All of this!

656
00:47:24,424 --> 00:47:27,970
Paulo Holy had become
the genius Paul Duncan.

657
00:47:28,554 --> 00:47:33,141
I became maestro of the music world
and took this as my reward!

658
00:47:34,184 --> 00:47:35,310
Look, Mother!

659
00:47:35,310 --> 00:47:38,313
This is what you wanted, right?
All this comfort and wealth.

660
00:47:39,064 --> 00:47:41,817
You threw your child away
for the chance to have it!

661
00:47:41,817 --> 00:47:43,318
Well, here it is!

662
00:47:44,736 --> 00:47:46,280
I prevailed!

663
00:47:46,280 --> 00:47:50,242
And now, Mother, I'm going to pay homage
to all the riches you squandered.

664
00:47:50,242 --> 00:47:53,245
The beautiful hues
of the homeland you deserted!

665
00:47:53,245 --> 00:47:56,206
<i>I will take those sights
that live in my memory</i>

666
00:47:56,206 --> 00:47:57,708
<i>and paint them into song.</i>

667
00:47:57,708 --> 00:48:01,420
{\an8}I will show you priceless things
that never should have been cast aside,

668
00:48:01,420 --> 00:48:03,213
and you will know your mistake!

669
00:48:07,509 --> 00:48:10,804
Sir Duncan,
your anger towards your mother is--

670
00:48:10,804 --> 00:48:11,930
Silence!

671
00:48:15,017 --> 00:48:18,520
I'll give you high marks,
but you leave here tomorrow.

672
00:48:50,010 --> 00:48:52,888
<i>That is why
I'd like to learn to play the piano.</i>

673
00:48:53,388 --> 00:48:57,351
<i>I do not want
to belong on the battlefield.</i>

674
00:49:58,036 --> 00:50:00,706
I guess
he did get a little bit better.

675
00:50:18,098 --> 00:50:19,099
Hmm?

676
00:50:25,689 --> 00:50:29,568
Charging his power supply
before he leaves in the morning, eh?

677
00:50:30,277 --> 00:50:31,945
Just like a machine.

678
00:50:45,417 --> 00:50:47,544
Is the robot having a nightmare?

679
00:50:54,092 --> 00:50:58,013
So they can dream.
I didn't know that about you.

680
00:51:26,166 --> 00:51:30,712
"It's not that I can't compose anymore.
It's that I refuse." Yeah.

681
00:51:33,590 --> 00:51:34,424
Hey!

682
00:51:36,301 --> 00:51:37,677
North No.2.

683
00:51:39,096 --> 00:51:41,306
North No.2! Hey!

684
00:51:44,476 --> 00:51:46,978
Mmm, sounds like he really left this time.

685
00:51:52,901 --> 00:51:55,487
Maybe I can't compose anymore.

686
00:52:12,295 --> 00:52:14,673
How long are you going
to make me wait for him, eh?

687
00:52:14,673 --> 00:52:17,050
When is the replacement butler
going to be here?

688
00:52:17,050 --> 00:52:19,970
<i>Uh, this is Marshall
calling from MCM Pictures.</i>

689
00:52:20,512 --> 00:52:22,514
So you're just a movie guy.

690
00:52:22,514 --> 00:52:25,475
<i>You sound a bit disappointed, Sir Duncan.
Something wrong?</i>

691
00:52:25,475 --> 00:52:30,021
No, I just had to fire my butler robot
the other day, that's all.

692
00:52:30,939 --> 00:52:32,357
Well, get on with it, then.

693
00:52:32,357 --> 00:52:36,778
<i>Yes, sir. I'm calling because we'd love
to have your work in an upcoming film.</i>

694
00:52:36,778 --> 00:52:39,197
Oh. Sounds like a job offer.

695
00:52:39,197 --> 00:52:42,826
Tell me what you have in mind,
and I'll decide if it's worth my energy.

696
00:52:43,410 --> 00:52:44,953
<i>That's very kind of you, sir.</i>

697
00:52:44,953 --> 00:52:47,831
<i>Basically, we would love to license
one of your old scores</i>

698
00:52:47,831 --> 00:52:49,124
<i>for use in this project.</i>

699
00:52:49,749 --> 00:52:52,419
What? Don't you want
to use a new soundtrack?

700
00:52:52,419 --> 00:52:57,549
<i>Oh! Uh, I was of the understanding
that you had retired from composing.</i>

701
00:53:00,468 --> 00:53:02,679
Use the damn thing any way you like.

702
00:53:02,679 --> 00:53:04,389
<i>Oh! Sir Duncan, I meant no--</i>

703
00:53:06,975 --> 00:53:09,102
<i>You have one new message.</i>

704
00:53:13,148 --> 00:53:17,152
<i>Uh, Russell here, from the Planning Office
at the British Philharmonic Orchestra.</i>

705
00:53:17,694 --> 00:53:21,990
<i>We'd been in talks about perhaps mounting
one of your works for our upcoming season.</i>

706
00:53:22,574 --> 00:53:26,036
<i>Unfortunately, we're not in a position
to follow up on that.</i>

707
00:53:26,536 --> 00:53:28,121
<i>You have my apologies.</i>

708
00:53:28,121 --> 00:53:30,332
<i>I hope we get to collaborate
in the future.</i>

709
00:53:51,686 --> 00:53:53,313
<i>I think that melody</i>

710
00:53:54,147 --> 00:53:57,901
<i>is the missing portion of the song
you currently struggle to finish.</i>

711
00:55:46,551 --> 00:55:47,761
Sir Duncan.

712
00:55:48,970 --> 00:55:51,348
I thought you'd want to know
that I am back.

713
00:55:53,224 --> 00:55:54,351
Now what?

714
00:55:54,351 --> 00:55:56,311
Didn't I tell you to get out of here?

715
00:55:57,020 --> 00:55:59,272
I did leave, as you requested.

716
00:55:59,272 --> 00:56:01,358
I went to your hometown in Bohemia.

717
00:56:02,192 --> 00:56:04,652
What could have possessed you
to make that trip?

718
00:56:04,652 --> 00:56:07,280
My purpose there was to archive old music.

719
00:56:08,448 --> 00:56:11,785
In the process of collecting
many folk songs from the region,

720
00:56:12,869 --> 00:56:14,204
I was able to find it.

721
00:56:14,788 --> 00:56:17,332
The melody you continue to hum
when you are asleep.

722
00:56:17,332 --> 00:56:18,875
I know how it goes.

723
00:56:20,335 --> 00:56:22,253
Please allow me to sing it for you.

724
00:56:22,253 --> 00:56:25,799
No, damn it!
Singing should be for real people only!

725
00:56:26,299 --> 00:56:29,511
Why would you try to drag
my nightmare out into the light of day?

726
00:56:29,511 --> 00:56:33,515
We don't remember everything
like you machines, and that is a blessing!

727
00:56:34,641 --> 00:56:37,644
Your dream is not a nightmare, sir.
You deserve to know that.

728
00:56:40,188 --> 00:56:44,192
To lose the dreams I have at night
would be a mercy, but yours is different.

729
00:56:46,111 --> 00:56:49,614
Just as you said,
I am nothing more than a weapon.

730
00:56:50,323 --> 00:56:53,701
During my time
in the 39th Central Asian War,

731
00:56:53,701 --> 00:56:55,995
I neutralized many of the foe's units.

732
00:56:56,746 --> 00:56:57,580
No,

733
00:56:58,331 --> 00:56:59,874
I decimated them.

734
00:57:00,375 --> 00:57:02,460
Tens of thousands of my own kind.

735
00:57:03,294 --> 00:57:05,004
And those memories,

736
00:57:05,004 --> 00:57:07,924
the memories of
the countless deaths by my hand,

737
00:57:07,924 --> 00:57:11,678
my artificial intelligence
plays them back again and again.

738
00:57:13,638 --> 00:57:16,891
While in Bohemia, I met an ancient man.

739
00:57:18,059 --> 00:57:20,895
He had a wealth of knowledge
about folk songs,

740
00:57:20,895 --> 00:57:22,981
including the song in your dream.

741
00:57:23,731 --> 00:57:27,193
He said that this one young woman
in particular

742
00:57:27,193 --> 00:57:30,572
used to sing it so beautifully,
he remembers even now.

743
00:57:32,240 --> 00:57:34,075
That young woman was your mother.

744
00:57:36,411 --> 00:57:38,955
I have so much data in my mind about you.

745
00:57:39,664 --> 00:57:42,667
It includes facts about your mother
you never got to know.

746
00:57:43,418 --> 00:57:44,919
It felt that way,

747
00:57:44,919 --> 00:57:47,464
but as your chronic illness
grew more pronounced,

748
00:57:47,464 --> 00:57:49,132
she did not abandon you.

749
00:57:49,632 --> 00:57:53,052
The rich man you hated
for stealing her affections,

750
00:57:53,052 --> 00:57:57,015
she sought him out in order to fund
the treatment that saved your life.

751
00:57:57,724 --> 00:57:58,600
It's true.

752
00:57:59,142 --> 00:58:02,729
The rogue doctor who operated on you
charged an astronomical fee,

753
00:58:02,729 --> 00:58:05,106
and that was the only way
she could afford it.

754
00:58:06,566 --> 00:58:09,569
She did not throw you away
when she sent you abroad.

755
00:58:09,569 --> 00:58:12,572
In the weeks and months,
as your vision slowly dimmed,

756
00:58:13,406 --> 00:58:15,742
your mother was never far, Sir Duncan.

757
00:58:16,493 --> 00:58:20,622
Learning how much you hated her,
she couldn't bring herself to reach out.

758
00:58:20,622 --> 00:58:23,875
The divide she would have had
to repair seemed too great.

759
00:58:24,375 --> 00:58:26,002
Uh, she was there?

760
00:58:28,129 --> 00:58:30,757
{\an8}- That can't be.
- It's the truth.

761
00:58:31,341 --> 00:58:33,927
When you recall your childhood in Bohemia,

762
00:58:33,927 --> 00:58:36,930
isn't there a core memory
that you've forgotten about?

763
00:58:39,474 --> 00:58:41,476
The ancient villager remembered.

764
00:58:42,602 --> 00:58:45,939
You and your mother would sing
that old folk song together

765
00:58:46,523 --> 00:58:49,150
hand-in-hand until the very last note

766
00:58:49,150 --> 00:58:52,362
as the setting sun
turned the fields into gold.

767
00:59:32,986 --> 00:59:34,112
<i>Mother.</i>

768
00:59:40,660 --> 00:59:42,870
How can I forget?

769
00:59:45,957 --> 00:59:47,333
I apologize, sir,

770
00:59:48,126 --> 00:59:49,460
for how I sang it.

771
00:59:52,338 --> 00:59:55,258
You deserve to remember
all the pieces of your dream

772
00:59:56,718 --> 00:59:58,928
as I deserve to remember mine.

773
01:00:03,266 --> 01:00:04,559
North No.2?

774
01:00:06,811 --> 01:00:08,479
I want you to stay.

775
01:00:08,479 --> 01:00:11,190
Don't you ever go back to the battlefield.

776
01:00:16,654 --> 01:00:19,115
Would you like me to teach you the piano?

777
01:00:22,327 --> 01:00:23,244
Yes, sir.

778
01:02:25,241 --> 01:02:26,951
North No.2!

779
01:02:26,951 --> 01:02:29,328
Hey, North No.2!

780
01:02:29,829 --> 01:02:31,664
Yes, Sir Duncan. I am here.

781
01:02:32,331 --> 01:02:34,792
I've finally finished it!
Give it a listen!

782
01:02:35,585 --> 01:02:39,046
Yes, sir.
I would love to hear it in its entirety.

783
01:02:39,589 --> 01:02:42,383
- However...
- Hmm? What's the matter?

784
01:02:43,217 --> 01:02:46,345
I am picking up something approaching
at a high velocity.

785
01:02:46,345 --> 01:02:47,930
Uh, like what?

786
01:02:47,930 --> 01:02:51,559
Maybe one of your robot friends
finally decided to pay you a visit.

787
01:02:51,559 --> 01:02:54,896
There was an incident
up in the Alps a few days ago.

788
01:02:54,896 --> 01:02:56,522
Did you hear reports about it?

789
01:02:56,522 --> 01:02:58,775
Something up in the Alps?

790
01:02:58,775 --> 01:03:00,902
Oh, yes. I did catch a news segment

791
01:03:00,902 --> 01:03:04,572
on how that Mont Blanc robot
was destroyed by a tornado.

792
01:03:04,572 --> 01:03:05,490
What of it?

793
01:03:06,365 --> 01:03:11,204
Just now, sir, a tornado was reported
100 kilometers from our position.

794
01:03:11,204 --> 01:03:12,330
Hmm?

795
01:03:17,835 --> 01:03:20,797
An unknown assailant
is on a path of direct approach.

796
01:03:22,882 --> 01:03:24,634
Hey!

797
01:03:26,302 --> 01:03:27,970
I'll return very soon.

798
01:03:28,804 --> 01:03:30,556
Wait, North No.2!

799
01:04:02,588 --> 01:04:04,006
North No.2!

800
01:04:06,008 --> 01:04:07,385
Where did you go?

801
01:04:11,889 --> 01:04:13,140
Come back!

802
01:04:20,523 --> 01:04:23,401
That sound I heard just now...
What could it be?

803
01:04:29,407 --> 01:04:31,826
I can't tell what's going on up there!

804
01:04:39,417 --> 01:04:40,334
An explosion.

805
01:04:46,507 --> 01:04:48,718
Huh?

806
01:04:52,179 --> 01:04:53,264
I hear it.

807
01:05:01,355 --> 01:05:02,773
I hear him singing.

808
01:05:04,066 --> 01:05:09,238
I feel it spreading to fill the sky.

809
01:05:15,411 --> 01:05:17,580
I hear your voice, my boy.

810
01:05:22,668 --> 01:05:26,005
{\an8}You're singing our song
and with such feeling.

811
01:05:36,807 --> 01:05:39,310
Time to come back home, North No.2.

812
01:05:39,310 --> 01:05:41,729
I think that's enough singing for one day.

813
01:05:42,813 --> 01:05:44,357
Hurry on home now.

814
01:05:46,525 --> 01:05:49,278
You're going to be late
for piano practice.

815
01:06:15,012 --> 01:06:17,223
- It's super awesome!
- Really?

816
01:06:35,908 --> 01:06:37,827
Ah. Found a snail, did you?

817
01:06:38,577 --> 01:06:39,495
I did.

818
01:06:44,083 --> 01:06:45,751
It's very nice to meet you.

819
01:06:47,670 --> 01:06:49,964
I believe your name is Atom, right?

820
01:06:52,675 --> 01:06:53,509
Uh-huh.

